Note:
XML Lexer - Tokenizes XML input

This file provides complete lexical analysis for XML 1.0/1.1, handling:
- Elements (opening, closing, self-closing tags)
- Attributes with quoted values
- Text content
- Comments
- CDATA sections
- Processing instructions
- Entity references
- Namespaces

XML Token Types:
- TAG_OPEN - < (start of opening tag)
- TAG_CLOSE - > (end of tag)
- TAG_SELF_CLOSE - /> (self-closing tag end)
- TAG_CLOSE_OPEN - </ (start of closing tag)
- EQUALS - = (attribute assignment)
- NAME - element/attribute names
- STRING - attribute values
- TEXT - text content between tags
- COMMENT - <!-- ... -->
- CDATA - <![CDATA[...]]>
- PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION - <?...?>
- ENTITY - &entity;

Features:
- Complete XML 1.0 specification support
- Namespace handling (prefix:localName)
- Entity reference detection
- Line/column position tracking
- Error reporting with context
- Unicode support

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XML Token Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0
Constant TOKEN_ERROR as Integer is 1

Constant TOKEN_TAG_OPEN as Integer is 10           Note: <
Constant TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE as Integer is 11          Note: >
Constant TOKEN_TAG_SELF_CLOSE as Integer is 12     Note: />
Constant TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE_OPEN as Integer is 13     Note: </

Constant TOKEN_EQUALS as Integer is 20              Note: =
Constant TOKEN_NAME as Integer is 21                Note: element/attribute name
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 22              Note: attribute value
Constant TOKEN_TEXT as Integer is 23                Note: text content

Constant TOKEN_COMMENT as Integer is 30             Note: <!-- comment -->
Constant TOKEN_CDATA as Integer is 31               Note: <![CDATA[...]]>
Constant TOKEN_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 32  Note: <?...?>
Constant TOKEN_ENTITY as Integer is 33              Note: &entity;

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XML Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML tokens carry the same tag-plus-view-plus-position shape as other frontend lexers; the lexeme pointer references heap storage (not the source) because content like attribute values and text have had entity references decoded into fresh buffers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five 8-byte fields: type discriminator, owned lexeme pointer, lexeme byte length, source line (1-indexed), source column (1-indexed).
@End Implementation

Type called "XMLToken":
    token_type as Integer       Note: TOKEN_* constant
    lexeme as Integer           Note: Pointer to string value
    lexeme_length as Integer    Note: Length of lexeme
    line as Integer             Note: Line number (1-indexed)
    column as Integer           Note: Column number (1-indexed)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XML Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML tokenization is context-sensitive: "<" and ">" delimit tag-internal regions where attribute/value tokens appear, while text and entity references appear between tags. Tracking in_tag as a flag is enough state to make next_token's dispatch unambiguous without backtracking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Seven 8-byte slots: source pointer, source length, byte cursor, current line, current column, in_tag flag, and an owned error_message pointer (or 0).
@End Implementation

Type called "XMLLexer":
    source as Integer           Note: Source code string
    source_length as Integer    Note: Length of source
    position as Integer         Note: Current position in source
    line as Integer             Note: Current line (1-indexed)
    column as Integer           Note: Current column (1-indexed)
    in_tag as Integer           Note: Boolean: 1 if inside a tag
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message if TOKEN_ERROR
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Starting line=1 column=1 in_tag=0 mirrors XML's natural state at the start of a document - outside any tag - so every subsequent dispatch decision is correct without explicit boot-strap.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 56 bytes; null-check. Measure source length. Store source / length, position=0, line=1, column=1, in_tag=0, error_message=0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_xml_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create XML lexer for source code

    Let lexer_size be 56  Note: XMLLexer: 7 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Note: Initialize lexer state
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0   Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1   Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1   Note: column = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0   Note: in_tag = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 0   Note: error_message = null

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer owns its error_message buffer; destruction must release it to prevent the standard "tokenisation failed and lexer discarded" leak.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-check the lexer. Read the error_message pointer at offset 48; if non-null deallocate. Deallocate the lexer block.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_xml_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy XML lexer

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Free error message if exists
    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Access and Manipulation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Every scan_* helper begins with one or more peeks; returning 0 at end-of-source lets callers compare against expected delimiters without an explicit bound check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read position and source_length. If position >= source_length return 0. Otherwise return source[position] as a byte value.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cursor mutation must also update line and column for diagnostics; concentrating that bookkeeping here guarantees no scan_* helper forgets it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Peek the current character; on EOF return 0. Increment position. If the char is '\n' (10), increment line and reset column to 1; otherwise increment column. Return the character.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next character and return it

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

    If char is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Update position
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Note: Update line/column tracking
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1
    Otherwise:
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column
    End If

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-character delimiters like "<!--", "<![CDATA[", "-->" need 1-, 2-, or 3-character lookahead; parameterising the offset keeps every dispatch site brief.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compute position+offset; if out of bounds return 0; otherwise return source[position+offset] as a byte value.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_ahead" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek ahead offset characters without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let look_pos be position plus offset

    If look_pos is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, look_pos

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML whitespace per the spec is exactly space, tab, line feed, and carriage return; explicit per-character comparisons match the spec without depending on locale.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Return 1 for ASCII 32 (space), 9 (tab), 10 (LF), or 13 (CR); 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is XML whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:  Note: carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
XML 1.0 NameStartChar admits letters, underscore, and colon (the colon is reserved by the namespace spec but is syntactically permitted here so namespace prefixes survive scanning).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Return 1 for ASCII a-z (97-122), A-Z (65-90), underscore (95), or colon (58); 0 otherwise. This is the ASCII subset of the full XML NameStartChar production - sufficient for syntax-driven lexing.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_name_start_char" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character can start an XML name

    Note: Letters
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
        If char is less than or equal to 90:  Note: 'Z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
        If char is less than or equal to 122:  Note: 'z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Underscore and colon (for namespaces)
    If char is equal to 95:  Note: _
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
XML NameChar extends NameStartChar with digits, hyphen, and dot; layering on top of is_name_start_char keeps the alphabet definition centrally located.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Return 1 if is_name_start_char(char) returns 1, or if char is in 48..57 (digit), or char is 45 (hyphen), or char is 46 (dot); 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_name_char" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character can continue an XML name

    If proc is_name_start_char with char is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Digits
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Hyphen and dot
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Every scan_* helper produces tokens via this constructor so the XMLToken layout is defined in exactly one site; future field additions (e.g. byte-offset for diagnostics) only touch one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 40 bytes (five 8-byte slots) and populate token_type, lexeme, length, line, column in order.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create XML token

    Let token_size be 40  Note: XMLToken: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Error tokens must record both the source position at the failure point and a copy of the message that survives lexer destruction; storing the message in the lexer too lets external diagnostic code retrieve it via the lexer pointer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read current line and column. Allocate length+1 bytes for the message, copy and null-terminate, store the pointer in the lexer at offset 48. Build a TOKEN_ERROR token carrying the original (not owned-copy) message pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_error_token" takes lexer as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create error token with message

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Store error message in lexer
    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let error_msg be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If error_msg is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with error_msg, 0, message, 0, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with error_msg, msg_length, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, error_msg
    End If

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ERROR, message, msg_length, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Name Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML element and attribute names follow the NameStartChar + NameChar* production where colons are reserved by the namespace spec as the "prefix:localName" separator; lexing names as one token (colons included) defers namespace splitting to a downstream pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a 256-byte name buffer. Verify the first character is a NameStartChar; on failure emit an error token. Copy the first char into the buffer, advance. Loop consuming NameChar bytes into the buffer (with overflow check). Null-terminate and emit TOKEN_NAME.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
The 256-byte buffer caps element/attribute name length; longer names are silently truncated. Production hardening should grow the buffer dynamically or surface an error.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scan_name" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan XML element or attribute name

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let buffer_size be 256
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    Note: First character must be name start char
    Let first_char be proc peek_char from lexer

    If proc is_name_start_char with first_char is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Invalid name start character"
    End If

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, first_char
    Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Note: Continue with name characters
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If proc is_name_char with char is equal to 1:
            If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char from lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break  Note: Name too long
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NAME, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Entity Reference Decoding
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML entity references "&name;" / "&#NNNN;" / "&#xHHHH;" embed characters that the rest of the lexer must not see as syntax; resolving them inline (numeric references with full UTF-8 encoding, plus the five built-in named entities) lets text and attribute scanners treat their output as plain bytes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consume the leading '&'. If '#' follows, distinguish decimal vs hex (after optional 'x'), accumulate digits until ';', then emit UTF-8 bytes for the codepoint (1-4 bytes depending on value range). Otherwise read alphanumeric bytes until ';' and compare against "amp" -> 38, "lt" -> 60, "gt" -> 62, "quot" -> 34, "apos" -> 39; write the resolved byte. Returns the new buffer_pos or -1 on any error (unterminated, unknown entity, invalid digit, buffer overflow).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) in the entity reference length; bounded by the 32-byte entity-name buffer cap.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
The entity-name buffer caps at 31 bytes preventing arbitrary-length names from consuming memory. Numeric references can produce arbitrary Unicode codepoints; the caller must ensure the surrounding buffer is large enough for the resulting UTF-8 bytes.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "decode_entity_reference" takes lexer as Integer, buffer as Integer, buffer_pos as Integer, buffer_size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Decode entity reference and write decoded character(s) to buffer

    Note: Current position is on '&', advance past it
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Note: Scan entity name until ';'
    Let entity_name_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Let entity_name_pos be 0

    If entity_name_buffer is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

    Note: Check for numeric character reference
    If char is equal to 35:  Note: # (&#NNNN; or &#xHHHH;)
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Set char to proc peek_char from lexer

        Let is_hex be 0
        Let value be 0

        Note: Check for hex format
        If char is equal to 120:  Note: 'x' (&#xHHHH;)
            Set is_hex to 1
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
        End If

        Note: Parse numeric value
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            If char is equal to 59:  Note: ; (end of reference)
                proc advance_char from lexer
                Break
            End If

            If char is equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Layout with entity_name_buffer
                Return -1  Note: Unterminated entity reference
            End If

            Note: Parse digit
            Let digit_value be -1

            If is_hex is equal to 1:
                Note: Hex digit
                If char is greater than or equal to 48:
                    If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: 0-9
                        Set digit_value to char minus 48
                    End If
                End If

                If char is greater than or equal to 65:
                    If char is less than or equal to 70:  Note: A-F
                        Set digit_value to char minus 65 plus 10
                    End If
                End If

                If char is greater than or equal to 97:
                    If char is less than or equal to 102:  Note: a-f
                        Set digit_value to char minus 97 plus 10
                    End If
                End If

                If digit_value is not equal to -1:
                    Set value to value multiplied by 16 plus digit_value
                Otherwise:
                    proc deallocate from Layout with entity_name_buffer
                    Return -1  Note: Invalid hex digit
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Note: Decimal digit
                If char is greater than or equal to 48:
                    If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: 0-9
                        Set digit_value to char minus 48
                        Set value to value multiplied by 10 plus digit_value
                    Otherwise:
                        proc deallocate from Layout with entity_name_buffer
                        Return -1  Note: Invalid decimal digit
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    proc deallocate from Layout with entity_name_buffer
                    Return -1
                End If
            End If

            proc advance_char from lexer
            Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with entity_name_buffer

        Note: Write character value to buffer with proper UTF-8 encoding
        If value is less than 128:
            Note: ASCII - single byte
            If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, value
                Return buffer_pos plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return -1
            End If

        Otherwise If value is less than 2048:
            Note: UTF-8 2-byte sequence (U+0080 to U+07FF)
            Let byte1 be 192 plus value divided by 64
            Let byte2 be 128 plus value modulo by 64

            If buffer_pos plus 1 is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, byte1
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos plus 1, byte2
                Return buffer_pos plus 2
            Otherwise:
                Return -1
            End If

        Otherwise If value is less than 65536:
            Note: UTF-8 3-byte sequence (U+0800 to U+FFFF)
            Set byte1 to 224 plus value divided by 4096
            Let remainder1 be value modulo by 4096
            Set byte2 to 128 plus remainder1 divided by 64
            Let byte3 be 128 plus remainder1 modulo by 64

            If buffer_pos plus 2 is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, byte1
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos plus 1, byte2
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos plus 2, byte3
                Return buffer_pos plus 3
            Otherwise:
                Return -1
            End If

        Otherwise:
            Note: UTF-8 4-byte sequence (U+10000 to U+10FFFF)
            Set byte1 to 240 plus value divided by 262144
            Set remainder1 to value modulo by 262144
            Set byte2 to 128 plus remainder1 divided by 4096
            Let remainder2 be remainder1 modulo by 4096
            Set byte3 to 128 plus remainder2 divided by 64
            Let byte4 be 128 plus remainder2 modulo by 64

            If buffer_pos plus 3 is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, byte1
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos plus 1, byte2
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos plus 2, byte3
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos plus 3, byte4
                Return buffer_pos plus 4
            Otherwise:
                Return -1
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Named entity reference - scan entity name
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        If char is equal to 59:  Note: ; (end of reference)
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with entity_name_buffer
            Return -1  Note: Unterminated entity reference
        End If

        If entity_name_pos is less than 31:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with entity_name_buffer, entity_name_pos, char
            Set entity_name_pos to entity_name_pos plus 1
        Otherwise:
            proc deallocate from Layout with entity_name_buffer
            Return -1  Note: Entity name too long
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
        Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate entity name
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with entity_name_buffer, entity_name_pos, 0

    Note: Decode standard entities
    Let decoded_char be 0

    Note: Check for &amp; (38 = '&')
    Let is_amp be proc string_equals_literal with entity_name_buffer, "amp"
    If is_amp is equal to 1:
        Set decoded_char to 38
    End If

    Note: Check for &lt; (60 = '<')
    Let is_lt be proc string_equals_literal with entity_name_buffer, "lt"
    If is_lt is equal to 1:
        Set decoded_char to 60
    End If

    Note: Check for &gt; (62 = '>')
    Let is_gt be proc string_equals_literal with entity_name_buffer, "gt"
    If is_gt is equal to 1:
        Set decoded_char to 62
    End If

    Note: Check for &quot; (34 = '"')
    Let is_quot be proc string_equals_literal with entity_name_buffer, "quot"
    If is_quot is equal to 1:
        Set decoded_char to 34
    End If

    Note: Check for &apos; (39 = "'")
    Let is_apos be proc string_equals_literal with entity_name_buffer, "apos"
    If is_apos is equal to 1:
        Set decoded_char to 39
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with entity_name_buffer

    Note: Check if we found a valid entity
    If decoded_char is equal to 0:
        Return -1  Note: Unknown entity reference
    End If

    Note: Write decoded character to buffer
    If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, decoded_char
        Return buffer_pos plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Return -1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Entity-name comparison against the five built-in entities needs a null-terminated string equality check; an inline byte loop avoids depending on StringCore for this hot path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk both strings in lockstep. On byte mismatch return 0. On simultaneous null terminator return 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_equals_literal" takes str as Integer, literal as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare string with string literal

    Let index be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, index
        Let char2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with literal, index

        If char1 is not equal to char2:
            Return 0
        End If

        If char1 is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: Both strings ended at same position
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Scanning (Attribute Values)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML attribute values are quoted with either '"' or "'" and may contain entity references which must be resolved before storage; parameterising the quote character lets the same routine handle both delimiters with consistent entity decoding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skip the opening quote. Allocate a 1024-byte buffer. Loop until the matching quote: on EOF emit error, on '&' delegate to decode_entity_reference (which updates the buffer), otherwise copy the byte. Null-terminate and emit TOKEN_STRING.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
The 1024-byte buffer is a fixed cap; values longer than 1024 bytes are silently truncated. The entity-reference decoder is the only path that can write multiple bytes per input character.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scan_string" takes lexer as Integer, quote_char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan quoted string (attribute value)

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip opening quote
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Let buffer_size be 1024
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Unterminated string"
        End If

        If char is equal to quote_char:  Note: Closing quote
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Break
        End If

        Note: Handle entity references in attribute values
        If char is equal to 38:  Note: bitwise and (entity reference)
            Let new_buffer_pos be proc decode_entity_reference with lexer, buffer, buffer_pos, buffer_size

            If new_buffer_pos is equal to -1:
                proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Invalid entity reference in attribute"
            End If

            Set buffer_pos to new_buffer_pos
        Otherwise:
            If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Text Content Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Text content between tags forms a TOKEN_TEXT lexeme; the scan terminates either at EOF or when '<' is seen (which next_token will handle), and entity references must be resolved into the buffer so consumers see decoded text.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a 2048-byte text buffer. Loop until EOF or '<': on '&' delegate to decode_entity_reference; otherwise copy the byte. Null-terminate and emit TOKEN_TEXT.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
2048-byte buffer cap; longer text runs truncate silently. Entity references behave per the standard set.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scan_text" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan text content between tags

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let buffer_size be 2048
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 60:  Note: is less than (start of tag)
            Break
        End If

        Note: Handle entity references in text
        If char is equal to 38:  Note: bitwise and (entity reference)
            Let new_buffer_pos be proc decode_entity_reference with lexer, buffer, buffer_pos, buffer_size

            If new_buffer_pos is equal to -1:
                proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Invalid entity reference in text"
            End If

            Set buffer_pos to new_buffer_pos
        Otherwise:
            If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TEXT, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comment Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
"<!-- ... -->" comments are passed through to consumers that care about round-trip fidelity; recognising the closing "-->" requires two-character lookahead at every '-' byte.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skip the four-byte opening "<!--". Allocate a 1024-byte buffer. Loop: on EOF emit error; on '-' peek next two characters - if they are "->" consume the closing "-->" and break. Otherwise copy the byte. Null-terminate and emit TOKEN_COMMENT.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
1024-byte buffer cap; longer comments truncate silently.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scan_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan XML comment: <!-- comment -->

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip <!--
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: <
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: !
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: -
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: -

    Let buffer_size be 1024
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    Note: Scan until -->
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Unterminated comment"
        End If

        Note: Check for -->
        If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
            Let next1 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
            Let next2 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 2

            If next1 is equal to 45:  Note: -
                If next2 is equal to 62:  Note: >
                    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: -
                    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: -
                    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: >
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Note: Add character to buffer
        If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMENT, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CDATA Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
"<![CDATA[ ... ]]>" sections bypass XML's escape rules so their contents are taken verbatim; recognising the closing "]]>" requires two-character lookahead at every ']' byte.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skip the nine-byte opening "<![CDATA[". Allocate a 2048-byte buffer. Loop: on EOF emit error; on ']' peek the next two characters - if they are "]>" consume "]]>" and break. Otherwise copy the byte. Null-terminate and emit TOKEN_CDATA.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
2048-byte buffer cap; longer CDATA sections truncate silently.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scan_cdata" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan CDATA section: <![CDATA[...]]>

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip <![CDATA[
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: <
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: !
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: [
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: C
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: D
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: A
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: T
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: A
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: [

    Let buffer_size be 2048
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    Note: Scan until ]]>
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Unterminated CDATA"
        End If

        Note: Check for ]]>
        If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
            Let next1 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
            Let next2 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 2

            If next1 is equal to 93:  Note: ]
                If next2 is equal to 62:  Note: >
                    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: ]
                    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: ]
                    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: >
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Note: Add character to buffer
        If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CDATA, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Processing Instruction Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
"<?target instructions?>" PIs carry stylesheet references and processing directives; the closing "?>" needs only one-character lookahead at every '?'.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skip the two-byte opening "<?". Allocate a 1024-byte buffer. Loop: on EOF emit error; on '?' peek the next byte - if '>' consume "?>" and break. Otherwise copy the byte. Null-terminate and emit TOKEN_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
1024-byte buffer cap; longer PIs truncate silently.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "scan_processing_instruction" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan processing instruction: <?target instruction?>

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip <?
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: <
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: ?

    Let buffer_size be 1024
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Out of memory"
    End If

    Note: Scan until ?>
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Unterminated processing instruction"
        End If

        Note: Check for ?>
        If char is equal to 63:  Note: ?
            Let next be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

            If next is equal to 62:  Note: >
                proc advance_char from lexer  Note: ?
                proc advance_char from lexer  Note: >
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Note: Add character to buffer
        If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML tokenisation switches between two contexts: inside a tag (names, "=", quoted attribute values, "/>", ">"), and outside (text content, with "<" opening a new tag or comment or CDATA or PI). One in_tag flag drives the dispatch and toggles when delimiters are produced.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skip leading whitespace. Capture line/column. On EOF emit TOKEN_EOF. If "<" - peek next: "/" -> TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE_OPEN (set in_tag=1), "!" then "-" -> scan_comment, "!" then "[" -> scan_cdata, "?" -> scan_processing_instruction, otherwise -> TOKEN_TAG_OPEN (set in_tag=1). If ">" -> TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE (clear in_tag). If "/>" -> TOKEN_TAG_SELF_CLOSE (clear in_tag). Inside a tag: "=" -> TOKEN_EQUALS, '"' or "'" -> scan_string, NameStartChar -> scan_name, else error. Outside a tag: scan_text.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) dispatch per call; the per-character whitespace skip is amortised O(n) across the entire token stream.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Consumes untrusted XML source. The dispatcher only advances on recognised input or via scan_* helpers (which have their own bounds); unknown bytes inside tags emit error tokens to halt the parse cleanly.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next XML token

    Note: Skip whitespace
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If proc is_whitespace with char is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let in_tag be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Set char to proc peek_char from lexer

    Note: EOF
    If char is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, 0, line, column
    End If

    Note: Check for < (start of tag/comment/CDATA/PI)
    If char is equal to 60:  Note: <
        Let next be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        Note: Closing tag </
        If next is equal to 47:  Note: /
            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: <
            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: /
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 1  Note: in_tag = true
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE_OPEN, 0, 0, line, column
        End If

        Note: Comment <!--
        If next is equal to 33:  Note: !
            Let next2 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 2

            If next2 is equal to 45:  Note: minus (comment)
                Return proc scan_comment from lexer
            End If

            If next2 is equal to 91:  Note: [ (CDATA)
                Return proc scan_cdata from lexer
            End If
        End If

        Note: Processing instruction <?
        If next is equal to 63:  Note: ?
            Return proc scan_processing_instruction from lexer
        End If

        Note: Opening tag <
        proc advance_char from lexer
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 1  Note: in_tag = true
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TAG_OPEN, 0, 0, line, column
    End If

    Note: Check for > (end of tag)
    If char is equal to 62:  Note: >
        proc advance_char from lexer
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0  Note: in_tag = false
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE, 0, 0, line, column
    End If

    Note: Check for /> (self-closing tag)
    If char is equal to 47:  Note: /
        Set next to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        If next is equal to 62:  Note: >
            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: /
            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: >
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0  Note: in_tag = false
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TAG_SELF_CLOSE, 0, 0, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: Inside tag context
    If in_tag is equal to 1:
        Note: Equals sign for attributes
        If char is equal to 61:  Note: =
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EQUALS, 0, 0, line, column
        End If

        Note: Quoted string (attribute value)
        If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
            Return proc scan_string with lexer, 34
        End If

        If char is equal to 39:  Note: '
            Return proc scan_string with lexer, 39
        End If

        Note: Name (element or attribute)
        If proc is_name_start_char with char is equal to 1:
            Return proc scan_name from lexer
        End If

        Return proc create_error_token with lexer, "Unexpected character in tag"
    End If

    Note: Outside tag context - scan text content
    Return proc scan_text from lexer
End Process

Note: End of XML Lexer
